It's a bug.

```
if (onnxruntime_USE_DNNL)
```

We need to have the similar thing on the jni project.

issue.body:
**Description**: Adds the compile time flags which turn on providers back to the JNI compilation step. Also the recent build system change removed the versioning from the jar file name, this adds it back and updates the documentation appropriately.

**Motivation and Context**
- If it fixes an open issue, please link to the issue here. Fixes #3071

body: @tracysh model that we are using is Seq2Seq with LSTM encoder/decoder; I'm not sure that DNNL is faster - I'm trying to conduct a comparison using java but it seems that DNNL doesn't work there; If you have any benchmarks on MLAS vs DNNL for LSTM-RNN - I would appreciate it; also interesting to hear what CPU optimizations are possible for these model architectures; I was thinking about quantization to INT8 for instance
@slevental if you checkout the branch referenced in my PR (#3082) you can build the Java package with DNNL support.
